solutions.content:
**SHORTEST PATH OF A NODE FROM MULTIPLE SOURCES Concept**

1. Use `BFS` to compute distance from `node1 to every node` and from `node2 to every node` individually.
 2. Loop from `0 to n` nodes and return `the first node with smallest value of max(A[node],B[node])`   

**The question also highlighted a line -> `Note that edges may contain cycles.`**
But we should not care about it because our main goal is to get distance of all nodes from node1 and node2 which doesn't need any detection of cycle. why??
Because while computing distance from a single source we discard the visited node which prevents us  from getting stuck in a cycle.


**The question from which I learnt this concept**: 
[2203. Minimum Weighted Subgraph With the Required Paths](https://leetcode.com/contest/weekly-contest-284/problems/minimum-weighted-subgraph-with-the-required-paths/)  
but its a bit harder than this one.

The people who were not able to solve, pls don't feel demotivated, this question had a concept of finding **SHORTEST PATH OF A NODE FROM MULTIPLE SOURCES**.
I encourage you to solve this problem first and understand the concept and apply the same in the above question link as this is question is a prerequisite of the above link question.
This logic will also work if there are more than 2 sources nodes, we just need small changes in those cases.

**Updation**: Thanks to **@jaylenzhang19**
> We can use just check if distance of any neighbour is still INT_MAX in BFS. This way we can eliminate the use of visited vector.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/48966e27-a55a-4a74-9585-a65f579c18bd_1659253302.6357615.png)



`Time` - O(N)
`Space` - O(N)

# C++	
	int closestMeetingNode(vector<int>& e, int n1, int n2) {
        auto bfs=[&](int src, vector<int> &dist,vector<int>& edge,int n){
            queue<int> q;
            q.push(src);
            dist[src]=0;
            while(q.size()>0){
                auto p= q.front(); q.pop();
                if(edge[p]!=-1 and dist[edge[p]]==INT_MAX){
                   q.push(edge[p]);  
                   dist[edge[p]]= dist[p]+1;
                }
            }
        };
        int n= e.size();
        vector<int> A(n,INT_MAX), B(n,INT_MAX);
        bfs(n1,A,e,n);   bfs(n2,B,e,n);
        int res= INT_MAX, node=-1;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(A[i]==INT_MAX or B[i]==INT_MAX) continue;
            if(res>max(A[i],B[i])) node=i,res= max(A[i],B[i]);
        }
        return node;
    }

# Java

    void bfs(int src, int[] dist,int[] edge,int n){
        Queue<Integer> q= new LinkedList<>();
        q.add(src);
        dist[src]=0;
        while(q.size()>0){
            var p= q.remove();
            if(edge[p]!=-1 && dist[edge[p]]==Integer.MAX_VALUE){
                q.add(edge[p]);
                dist[edge[p]]= dist[p]+1;
            }
        }
    }

    public int closestMeetingNode(int[] e, int n1, int n2) {
        int n= e.length;
        int[] A= new int[n]; 
        int[] B= new int[n];
        Arrays.fill(A,Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        Arrays.fill(B,Integer.MAX_VALUE);

        //call bfs
        bfs(n1,A,e,n);
        bfs(n2,B,e,n);

        //get node with minimum value of distance
        int res= Integer.MAX_VALUE, node=-1;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(A[i]==Integer.MAX_VALUE || B[i]==Integer.MAX_VALUE) continue;
            if(res>Math.max(A[i],B[i])){
                node=i; 
                res= Math.max(A[i],B[i]);
            }
        }
        return node;
    }

