# Approach
We can actually use DFS to store the distance of every node from node1 & node2 and then traverse on those distances and minimise the maximum distance.
Below is the implementaion in C++ & JAVA.

# Code Explanation

We initialize several data structures:

1. ***distance_node1*** and ***distance_node2*** : vectors which store the distance of each node from node1 and node2, respectively.
2. ***visited*** is a boolean vector which keeps track of the nodes that have already been visited during the traversal.
3. ***adj*** is a vector of vectors used to store the *adjacency list* representation of the graph.

The adjacency list is constructed by looping through the "edges" vector. For each index i in "edges", the value of edges[i] is added to the adjacency list of i. If the value of edges[i] is -1, it is treated as a self-loop.

After that, we perform a Depth First Search (DFS) on the graph starting from ***"node1"*** to find the distance of each node from ***"node1"***. The DFS sets the visited flag of each visited node to true and updates the corresponding entry in the ***"distance_node1"*** vector.

Then the function performs another DFS starting from ***"node2"*** to find the distance of each node from ***"node2"*** in a similar way.

Finally, the function loops through all the nodes and finds the node with the minimum maximum distance from ***"node1"*** and ***"node2"*** and returns the index of that node. This node is the closest meeting point between ***"node1"*** and ***"node2"***.

# C++ Code
```
class Solution {
    // Function for Depth First Search
    void dfs(int i, vector<bool>& visited, vector<vector<int>>& adj, vector<int>& distance_node1, int dist)
    {
        // Marking the node visited
        visited[i]=true;
        // Storing the distance 
        distance_node1[i]=dist;
        // Checking the further nodes
        for (auto it: adj[i]) if (!visited[it]) dfs(it, visited, adj, distance_node1, dist+1);
    }
public:
    int closestMeetingNode(vector<int>& edges, int node1, int node2) {
        // Data structure to store Distance of nodes from node1 & node 2
        vector<int> distance_node1(edges.size(),1e6);
        vector<int> distance_node2(edges.size(),1e6);
        // Visited array to keep a traack of visited nodes
        vector<bool> visited(edges.size(),false);
        // Declaring Adjacency List
        vector<vector<int>> adj(edges.size());

        // Filling Adjacency List
        for (int i=0;i<edges.size();i++)
        {
            // Treating -1 as self loop
            if (edges[i]==-1) adj[i].push_back(i);
            else adj[i].push_back(edges[i]);
        }
        // Calling dfs to fill the distance needed for each node
        dfs(node1, visited, adj, distance_node1, 0);
        // Reset the visited array after first dfs call
        for (int i=0;i<edges.size();i++) visited[i]=false;
        // Calling dfs to fill the distance needed for each node
        dfs(node2, visited, adj, distance_node2, 0);

        int ans=1e6;
        // Keeping track of index
        int ind=-1;
        for (int i=0;i<edges.size();i++)
        {
            // Minimising the maximum distance of node from node1 & node2
