#### 1. Using DFS:
``` java []
class Solution {
    public int closestMeetingNode(int[] edges, int node1, int node2) {
        int n = edges.length;
        int[] dist1 = new int[n];   // to store the distances between node1 and other nodes
        int[] dist2 = new int[n];   // to store the distances between node2 and other nodes
        Arrays.fill(dist1, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        Arrays.fill(dist2, Integer.MAX_VALUE);

        // boolean arrays to mark our visits at each node
        boolean[] vis1 = new boolean[n];
        boolean[] vis2 = new boolean[n];

        // distance between nod1 and node1 is 0, so is for node2
        dist1[node1] = dist2[node2] = 0;        

        // Call the DFS methods
        dfs(edges, node1, dist1, vis1);
        dfs(edges, node2, dist2, vis2);

        int minDistNode = -1;   // to store our answer node
        // variable to store the min distance of our answer node from node1 & node2
        int minDistSoFar = Integer.MAX_VALUE;   
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            // take the max between the two distances
            int maxDistBetweenTwo = Math.max(dist1[i], dist2[i]);
            // if that max is lesser than minDistSoFar
            if (maxDistBetweenTwo < minDistSoFar) {
                minDistSoFar = maxDistBetweenTwo;   // that max becomes a candidate min distance
                minDistNode = i;    // that node becomes a candidate answer node
            }
        }

        return minDistNode;
    }

    private void dfs(int[] edges, int currNode, int[] dist, boolean[] visited) {
        visited[currNode] = true;           // we mark our visit
        int nextNode = edges[currNode];     // the node we are gonna visit
        // -1 indicates that there is no outgoing from our current node
        // also if visited already, we won't visit again
        if (nextNode != -1 && !visited[nextNode]) {
            visited[nextNode] = true;   // mark the next node's visit
            // distance for our new node 1 + distance we travelled to come to current node
            dist[nextNode] = 1 + dist[currNode]; 
            dfs(edges, nextNode, dist, visited);    // call DFS for the new node
        }
    }
}

// TC: O(2n), SC: O(n)
```
---
#### 2. Using BFS:
``` java []
class Solution {
    public int closestMeetingNode(int[] edges, int node1, int node2) {
        int n = edges.length;
        int[] dist1 = new int[n];   // to store the distances between node1 and other nodes
        int[] dist2 = new int[n];   // to store the distances between node2 and other nodes
        Arrays.fill(dist1, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        Arrays.fill(dist2, Integer.MAX_VALUE);

        // call the BFS for node1 and node2
        bfs(edges, node1, dist1);
        bfs(edges, node2, dist2);

        // the rest stays the same just like DFS
        int minDistNode = -1;
        int minDistSoFar = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int maxDistBetweenTwo = Math.max(dist1[i], dist2[i]);
            if (maxDistBetweenTwo < minDistSoFar) {
                minDistSoFar = maxDistBetweenTwo;
                minDistNode = i;
            }
        }

        return minDistNode;
    }

    private void bfs(int[] edges, int currNode, int[] dist) {
        Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
        q.offer(currNode);  // we push the current node

        boolean[] visited = new boolean[edges.length];
        visited[currNode] = true;   // we mark our visit at current node
        // distance between currNode and currrNode is 0
        dist[currNode] = 0; 
        // start the iteration
        while (!q.isEmpty()) {
            int curr = q.poll();    // pop out the last visited node
            int nextNode = edges[curr]; // the node we are going to visit next
            // -1 indicates that there is no outgoing from our current node
            // also if visited already, we won't visit again
            if (nextNode != -1 && !visited[nextNode]) {
                visited[nextNode] = true;  // mark the next node's visit
                // distance for our new node 1 + distance we travelled to come to current node
                dist[nextNode] = 1 + dist[curr];
                q.offer(nextNode);  // push the new node to the queue
            }
        }
    }
}

// TC: O(2n), SC: O(n)
```
---
#### We can space optimise our solution by getting rid of the boolean arrays to mark our visits.
If our distance array holds the value `Integer.MAX_VALUE` means distance for that index/node has not been updated yet. And it hasn't been updated means it wasn't visited.

So we would simply check if `dist[node] == Integer.MAX_VALUE`. 
If it's `true` means it wasn't visited, otherwise it was visited if `false`.

---
#### DFS:
``` java []
class Solution {
    public int closestMeetingNode(int[] edges, int node1, int node2) {
        int n = edges.length;
        int[] dist1 = new int[n];
        int[] dist2 = new int[n];
        Arrays.fill(dist1, Integer.MAX_VALUE); 
        Arrays.fill(dist2, Integer.MAX_VALUE);

        dist1[node1] = dist2[node2] = 0;

        dfs(edges, node1, dist1);
        dfs(edges, node2, dist2);

        int minDistNode = -1;
        int minDistSoFar = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int maxDistBetweenTwo = Math.max(dist1[i], dist2[i]);
            if (maxDistBetweenTwo < minDistSoFar) {
                minDistSoFar = maxDistBetweenTwo;
                minDistNode = i;
            }
        }

        return minDistNode;
    }

    private void dfs(int[] edges, int currNode, int[] dist) {
        int nextNode = edges[currNode];
        if (nextNode != -1 && dist[nextNode] == Integer.MAX_VALUE) {
            dist[nextNode] = 1 + dist[currNode];
            dfs(edges, nextNode, dist);
        }
    }
}
```
