solutions.content:
# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Use BFS to traverse in parallel from both `node1` and `node2`. Keep track of all the seen nodes from each starting node. Once we find a common node between the two sets we return the answer.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Use a single queue and BFS algorithm to traverse the graph is parallel from `node1` and `node2`.
2. Keep track of all the seen nodes so far from both starting nodes.
3. Each node has at most one directed neighbor. So we will process at most two nodes at each BFS level (one for each starting node).
4. If a node from one of the sets is already in the other set, remember it as a potential answer. The final answer is the minimum of the two nodes processed at the current BFS level that are present in both the sets.

