# Intuition
First. This is a BFS approach as we need to find the shortest path.
Second. We don't need a queue here as we've told there's **at most one** outgoing edge.
Finally. Don't need to find shortest path independently and count distance to each node, just move nodes towards to each other until they'll meet.

# Approach
Move simultaneously from both nodes towards to each other. Keep the track of each node. As soon as you find next node 1 at the track of the node 2 or node 2 at the track 1 - here is the answer. Also you can meet both at the same step, then choose the smallest.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int closestMeetingNode(int[] edges, int node1, int node2) {
        if (node1 == node2)
            return node1;
        HashSet<Integer> set1 = new HashSet<>();
        set1.add(node1);
        HashSet<Integer> set2 = new HashSet<>();
        set2.add(node2);
        while ((edges[node1] != -1 && !set1.contains(edges[node1])) || (edges[node2] != -1 && !set2.contains(edges[node2]))) {
            if (edges[node1] != -1 && !set1.contains(edges[node1])) {
                node1 = edges[node1];
                set1.add(node1);
            }
            if (edges[node2] != -1 && !set2.contains(edges[node2])) {
                node2 = edges[node2];
                set2.add(node2);
            }
            if (set1.contains(node2) && set2.contains(node1))
                return Math.min(node1, node2);
            if (set1.contains(node2))
                return node2;
            if (set2.contains(node1))
                return node1;
        }
        return -1;
    }
}
```

