# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
As we need to find the index of node which is at minimum of maximum distance from both the given nodes.
Lets say we have edges as [2, 2, 3, -1] and node1 = 0, node2 = 1.
We will calculate distance of each node from each of given nodes and then compare the maximums of each index. The index at which we will be getting the minimum of maximums from both distance array that index would be our resulting node.
For above :
```
mx = number_of_edges+1
distance_from_node1 = [0, mx, 1, 2]
distance_from_node1 = [mx, 0, 1, 2]
maximums_at_each_Node = [mx, mx, 1, 2]
```
Hence our resulting node will be 2 as we are getting the minimum of all maximums at that node.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Maintain two arrays for distances of each node from 2 given nodes.
2. For distance we can do simplified traversal as each node can have at max one outward edges.
3. During the traversal if we encounter the child having the edge to its parent i.e the child node of that child has distance less than the max distance, at that instance break the loop.
4. After computing distance we can compare them and return the index at which we are getting minimum of maximum distance.
# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
As we are iterating over nodes only thrice sepraterly. 
Hence $$O(n)$$ + $$O(n)$$ + $$O(n)$$ = $$O(3n)$$ = $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$
Here we are using two arrays of length n for distance computation.
Hence $$O(n)$$ + $$O(n)$$ = $$O(2n)$$ = $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int closestMeetingNode(vector<int>& edges, int node1, int node2) {
        int n = edges.size();
        vector<int> distance_from_node1(n+1, n+1), distance_from_node2(n+1, n+1);

        distance_from_node1[node1] = distance_from_node2[node2] = 0;

        int curr = node1, distance_traversed_sofar = 0;

        while(edges[curr] != -1)
        {
            curr = edges[curr];
            if(distance_from_node1[curr] != n+1)break;
            distance_from_node1[curr] = ++distance_traversed_sofar;
        }

        curr = node2;
        distance_traversed_sofar = 0;

        while(edges[curr] != -1)
        {
            curr = edges[curr];
            if(distance_from_node2[curr] != n+1)break;
            distance_from_node2[curr] = ++distance_traversed_sofar;
        }

        int ans = n+1, idx = -1;
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++)
        {
            if(ans > max(distance_from_node1[i],distance_from_node2[i]))
            {
                idx = i;
                ans = max(distance_from_node1[i],distance_from_node2[i]);
            }
        }

        return idx;
    }
};
