# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
In order to find intersecting node from 2 nodes solution, we will need to visit all nodes from `node1` and `node2`

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
DFS from both nodes, iterate over all visited nodes and check if it's visited by both nodes. If so take optimal one described in the Description

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
/**
 * @param {number[]} edges
 * @param {number} node1
 * @param {number} node2
 * @return {number}
 */
var closestMeetingNode = function(edges, node1, node2) {
    const dfs = (node, obj, cnt = 0) => {
        // Check if it's already visited - i.e. cyclic
        if(node === -1 || typeof(obj[node]) !== "undefined"){return;}
        obj[node] = cnt;

        dfs(edges[node], obj, cnt+1);
    }

    const from1 = {}
    const from2 = {};
    dfs(node1, from1)
    dfs(node2, from2)

    let mx = 0, ind = -1;
    Object.keys(from1).forEach(key=>{
        const costFrom1 = from1[key];
        const costFrom2 = from2[key];

        // check if `key` node is visited by node2 as well
        if(typeof costFrom2 !== "undefined"){
            if(ind===-1 
                || mx > Math.max(costFrom1, costFrom2) 
                || (mx === Math.max(costFrom1, costFrom2) && ind>key)
                ){
                mx = Math.max(costFrom1, costFrom2);
                ind = key;
            }
        }
    })

    return ind;
};
```

