# Intuition
###### Goal is to find a place for two friends to meet and go on a trip together. Friend 1 starting from node1 and Friend 2 starting from node2. Both are travelling from different paths with different road signs. Now they want to find the closest point where they can meet and do whatever they want to. We need a code to help them find the closest point where they can meet. 
###### So, make two lists for both of them and keep track of how far they will travel to each node/road sign. Then compare distances for both friends to reach any particular node  only if its possible for each of them to reach that particular node. When you find some node keep track of which one is the closest meeting point and return that node as answer. Again, I thought of it as the closest place for two friends to meet.

# Approach
1. Create two arrays ***p1*** and ***p2*** to keep track of distance of each node in the path from **node1** and **node2**.
2. Fill both arrays with -1 to indicate that distance is not defined as the node is not accessible.
3. Fill the array ***p1*** for **node1**.
4. Now while filling the array ***p2*** for **node2**, check if the current node ***i*** is accessible by **node1** or not.
5. If it is accessible by node1 and **node2**, compare the total distance from node1 and **node2** to the current node and if it shorter than the previous distance assign the node to result and if it is equal assign the node with smaller index to the answer(As per the problem statement).
6. Finally return the shortest distance node.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
The time complexity for this code is $$O(n)$$. Since it traverses the entire path once in both the iterations. Or you can say that time take by the code increases linearly depending on ``n`` or the size of ``edges`` array.

- Space complexity:
Space complexity is clearly $$O(n)$$ since we need two arrays ``p1``and ``p2`` to store the distances from each node.

# Code
```
class Solution {

    public int closestMeetingNode(int[] edges, int node1, int node2) {
        int n = edges.length;

        //Store path distances for every node from node1 and node2 
        int[] p1 = new int[n];
        int[] p2 = new int[n];

        //Fill array with -1, if any node is inaccessible by any of the two nodes, its distance is undefined(-1 here)
        Arrays.fill(p1, -1);
        Arrays.fill(p2, -1); 

        int res = -1; // -1 if no two common paths found
        int l_min = n; // Local Minima for every path to a common node

        //Storing path distances from node1 in p1 terminate the loop when the final node is reached i.e. edges[current] == -1
        for(int i = node1, d = 0; i != -1 && p1[i] == -1; i = edges[i], d++){

            p1[i] = d; 

        }
    	//Storing path distances from node2 in p2 terminate the loop when the final node is reached i.e. edges[current] == -1
        //Also comparing path distances to the current node from node1 and node2 if the node is accessible by both node1 and node2
        for(int i = node2, d = 0; i != -1 && p2[i] == -1; i = edges[i], d++){

            p2[i] = d;

            if(p1[i] != -1 && l_min >= Math.max(p1[i], p2[i])){

                res = Math.max(p1[i], p2[i]) == l_min ? Math.min(res, i) : i; // if equal return the node with smaller index
                l_min = Math.min(l_min, Math.max(p1[i], p2[i])); // compare and assign the local minimum value

            }
        }

        return res;
    }
}
```
# Similarity to BFS 

###### This code uses a modified version of BFS algorithm. BFS is an algorithm which traverses all the nodes at the current level before moving on to the next level. The algorithm starts at a particular node and explores all the neighboring nodes at the current depth level before moving to the next level.

###### In this code the graph is represented by an array of integers `edges` where each element `edges[i]` represents the next node in the graph from the current node which can be atmost 1 node(As per the problem statement). The code stores distances of node1/node2 from each node. It is like a combination of traversing the path and storing the distance in an array(like BFS) and comparing the values to find the closest meeting point(Which is not a traditional step in BFS).

# BFS Approach 
###### You can find explanation for this code and if you don't understand why or how this works I suggest you should watch Graph theory videos by William Fiset on YouTube. That guy is helping me a lot right now. I started learning graph theory from his videos last week only and its good, I can see improvement in my thinking and approach to problems related to graphs.
```
class Solution {
    int[] arr;
    public int closestMeetingNode(int[] edges, int node1, int node2) {
        arr = edges;
        int[] paths1 = solve(node1);
        int[] paths2 = solve(node2);
        int minDist = -1;
        int minDistTillNow = Integer.MAX_VALUE;

        for(int curr = 0; curr < edges.length; curr++){
            if(minDistTillNow > Math.max(paths1[curr], paths2[curr])) {
                minDist = curr;
                minDistTillNow = Math.max(paths1[curr],paths2[curr]);
            }
        }
        return minDist;
    }
    private int[] solve(int s){
        Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
        boolean[] visited = new boolean[arr.length];
        int[] paths = new int[arr.length];
        Arrays.fill(paths, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        paths[s] = 0;
        q.offer(s);
        while(!q.isEmpty()){
            int curr = q.poll();
            if(visited[curr]){
                continue;
            }
            visited[curr] = true;
            int neighbour = arr[curr];
            if(neighbour != -1 && !visited[neighbour]){
                paths[neighbour] = 1 + paths[curr];
                q.offer(neighbour);
            }

        }
        return paths;
    }
}
```

