# Intuition

Start BFS traversal in graph from `node1` and `node2`. We will maintain a `visitor` vector for storing visitor of node. At some point when the node is already visited but by someone else then this is one of our solution. 

Since its BFS traversal, we have to check for all nodes which are currently at the same level in queue and after that we will return the minimum index from them if exisits or -1.
# Approach

- Step 1 - Check if `node1` and `node2` are same then return any of them
- Step 2 - Initialize queue, visitor vector, ans and minStep.
- Step 3 - Start BFS traversal and store solution.
- Step 4 - Return minimum index if ans found otherwise return -1
- (See comments written in the code for better understanding)

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int closestMeetingNode(vector<int>& edges, int node1, int node2) {
        int n = edges.size();   // total nodes
        int ans = n+1;          // set to max value of index
        int minStep = -1;       // minStep required for ans

        vector<int> visitor(n, -1); // For storing visitor of node
        queue<pair<int,int>> q;     // For storing node and its level

        // {node-index, level}
        q.push({node1, 0}); 
        q.push({node2, 0});

        visitor[node1] = node1;
        visitor[node2] = node2;

        // BFS 
        while(!q.empty()) {
            int node = q.front().first;
            int step = q.front().second;
            q.pop();

            // neighbour of current node
            int next = edges[node];
            if(next != -1) {
                // if next is not visited then
                if(visitor[next] == -1) {
                    // Store (visitor of node) as its visitor
                    visitor[next] = visitor[node];
                    // Push next and its level to the queue
                    q.push({next, step + 1});
                } 
                // if next is visited but by someone else then check
                else if(visitor[next] != visitor[node] && 
                    (minStep == -1 || step == minStep)) {
                    // If its first node for ans then update minStep 
                    // and check all other nodes for same level
                    if(minStep == -1) minStep = step;
                    ans = min(ans, next);
                }
            }
        }
        // return ans
        if(ans == n+1) return -1;
        return ans;
    }
};
```

